and behavior of the binding force.

9
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:40,040
In addition to the baryons and
their resonances,

10
00:00:40,040 --> 00:00:42,260
which we have already treated
in the previous video,

11
00:00:42,260 --> 00:00:45,560
there are bound states between quarks and
antiquarks which we call mesons.

12
00:00:47,150 --> 00:00:50,640
If their quantum numbers are right,
they can be produced in vacuo

13
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:54,830
by a virtual photon,
as shown in this Feynman diagram.

14
00:00:55,850 --> 00:00:58,978
For light quarks,
their mass is dominated by binding energy.

15
00:00:58,978 --> 00:01:03,435
For heavy quarks, their mass is slightly
lower than the sum of the masses of

16
00:01:03,435 --> 00:01:05,380
the corresponding quark pair.

17
00:01:05,380 --> 00:01:07,730
An example is the production
of rho mesons,

18
00:01:07,730 --> 00:01:11,870
a bound state between light quarks,
which is shown in this Feynman diagram.

19
00:01:13,305 --> 00:01:17,455
Resonances can also appear as intermediate
states in hadronic reactions.

20
00:01:17,455 --> 00:01:22,105
In this case, there's obviously more
freedom regarding their quantum numbers.

21
00:01:22,105 --> 00:01:24,150
In general,
bound states between quarks and

22
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:28,435
antiquarks have a rather short lifetime,
especially if heavy quarks are involved.

23
00:01:28,435 --> 00:01:32,305
This is due to the substantial phase
space available for their decay.

24
00:01:34,420 --> 00:01:38,300
The energy dependence of
the electron-positron cross section around

25
00:01:38,300 --> 00:01:41,440
a resonance generally follows
a Breit-Wigner function,

26
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:44,180
which is shown in this equation.

27
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,570
M is the mass and
Gamma is the width of the resonance.

28
